# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: en-3
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:en-3/cen-workshop-agreement] A **CEN Workshop Agreement** (commonly abbreviated CWA) is a reference document from the European Committee for Standardization (CEN).
[src:en-3/cen-workshop-agreement] It is, by definition, not an official standard from the member organizations.
[src:en-3/cen-workshop-agreement] In the field of electronic signatures, several CWAs exist.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] A revised version was published in December 2014; it is identical to ISO/IEC Guide 71:2014.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] In 2000 ISO and IEC published the policy statement: "Addressing the needs of older persons and people with disabilities in standardization work".
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] This policy statement recognised the need to include the requirements of older persons and persons with disabilities during the development and revision of standards.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] The policy statement also recommended using ISO/IEC Guide 71, which would become available in 2001.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] ISO/IEC Guide 71:2001: *Guidelines for standardization to address the needs of older persons and people with disabilities* was published in 2001 and has been widely accepted: it has been used in Japan and was adopted by CEN and CENELEC as CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 (see below).
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] ISO/IEC Guide 71 was also made available in Braille and was the first ISO publication that was made available in this format.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] CEN and CENELEC adopted ISO/IEC Guide 71 as CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 as a result of Mandate M/283, which the European Commission gave to the three official European standardisation bodies, CEN, CENELEC and ETSI on 24 June 1999.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] Guide 6 is part of a wider framework that standardisation organisations can use to support the need for more accessible products and services.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] The ISO/IEC Policy Statement 2000 "Addressing the Needs of Older Persons and People with Disabilities in Standardization Work" already provided principles and considerations for ensuring that the needs of older persons and persons with disabilities are addressed in the standardisation process.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] ETSI, the third European standardisation body to which Mandate M/283 was addressed, did not adopt CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 but continued using ISO/IEC Guide 71 as a reference document.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] Since 2008 ISO/IEC Guide 71 has a supporting document: ISO/TR 22411:2008: *Ergonomics data and guidelines for the application of ISO/IEC Guide 71 to products and services to address the needs of older persons and persons with disabilities*.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] In December 2014 CEN and CENELEC adopted the revised ISO/IEC Guide 71: 2014 as CEN-CENELEC Guide 6:2014.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] This new version of Guide 6 is freely available on the website of CEN and CENELEC.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 is a document for participants in CEN technical bodies: Technical Committees or TCs, Working Groups or WGs, Task Forces, Workshops etcetera.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] These technical bodies are responsible for addressing the needs of persons with disabilities and older people in the standards, specifications, reports or other documents that they produce.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] 3. to raise awareness about the benefits of accessible design.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] The Guide consists of a few introductory sections followed by 10 other chapters which are called "clauses".
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] The most important chapters are described in the list below.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] Clause 7 and 8 provide tables that relate several types of clauses in a standard (for example, on packaging, the user interface and the built environment) to factors that need to be considered when addressing disabilities.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] Clause 9 provides descriptions of body functions or disabilities and their implications when using products and services.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] The last chapter is a bibliography that provides a list of resources for more specific guidance.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] In December 2001, CEN and CENELEC published CEN/CENELEC Guide 2: "CEN/CENELEC Guide 2: Consumer interests and the preparation of standards", which is a republication of CEN/CENELEC Memorandum 2 from 1977.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] This guide recommends member bodies of CEN and CENELEC to consult with consumer organisations when developing standards that are relevant to consumer interests.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] CEN/CENELEC Guide 2 is older than Guide 6 and therefore does not reference it.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] At the end of 2004, CEN adopted a "Mechanism on the use of the CEN/CENELEC Guide 6" According to ANEC it took two years to develop this mechanism and its adoption followed after "intense lobbying by ANEC".
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] When a standard is reviewed, the technical body can address the needs of older persons and persons with disabilities if necessary.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] When creating a new standard, these needs can be addressed during the standardisation work.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] When appropriate, a technical body can add a statement in the foreword of a standard that states where the needs of older persons and persons with disabilities have been addressed.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] The primary reference document that technical bodies should use when addressing the needs of older persons and persons with disabilities in their work is CEN/CENELEC Guide 6.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] CEN/CENELEC Guide 11: "Product information relevant to consumers - Guidelines for standard developers" was published in 2006 and refers to CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 for guidance on informational needs of people with disabilities and older people.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] In 2006 CEN sent a questionnaire on the use of Guide 6 to its technical committees.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] The results showed that 3 out of 275 CEN committees used the Guide 6.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] ANEC decided to propose to CEN how to take an initiative to change the situation.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] In 2007–2008, NEN - the Dutch standardisation organisation - and Standard Norge carried out a feasibility study within the European Mandate M/371.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] One of the findings was that the implementation of Guide 6 faced some difficulties.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] For this reason, NEN and CEN started an action to promote the use of Guide 6, and in December 2007 NEN proposed the installation of an CEN/CENELEC/BT/WG Accessibility for All.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] ANEC also supported the creation of such a working group.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] This led to the creation of the CEN/CENELEC/BT/WG *CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 Implementation Mechanism*.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] The working group held a preliminary meeting on 29 October 2008 and its first official meeting on 8 April 2009.
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] 2. representatives of older persons and persons with disabilities need training on the standardisation process (and CEN/CENELEC Guide 6).
[src:en-3/cenelec-guide-6] The European project USEM (User Empowerment in Standardisation) also used CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 in its training on standardisation for representatives of older persons and persons with disabilities.
[src:en-3/en-10027] Note that an increasing number of national European standards (DIN, AFNOR, UNE, UNI, etc.) and UK standards are being withdrawn and replaced by European Standards (EN).
[src:en-3/en-10027] This task is carried out by the Comité Européen de Normalisation (CEN) (European Committee for Standardization).
[src:en-3/en-10027] Steel specified by chemical composition.
[src:en-3/en-10027] The inclusion of a letter 'G' before the code indicates the steel is specified in the form of a casting.
[src:en-3/en-10027] Basic grade designations for category 1 steels consist of a single letter (designating application) then a number signifying the mechanical property (often yield strength) dictated in the standard for that application designation.
[src:en-3/en-10027] For some application designations another letter is included before the property value, this number is used to indicate any special requirements or conditions.
[src:en-3/en-10027] These additional letters and values depend entirely on the application of the steel and are specified in the standard and far too numerous to mention here.
[src:en-3/en-10027] The next set of 3 digits gives the steel's minimum yield strength.
[src:en-3/en-10027] So S355 has a minimum yield strength of 355 MPa for the smallest thickness range covered by the relevant standard – i.e.
[src:en-3/en-10027] Below is a table indicating the most common application codes.
[src:en-3/en-10027] In addition to the above category codes there are symbols that can be added to the grade code to identify any additional compositional requirements, delivery conditions, mechanical properties, &c.
[src:en-3/en-10027] These values depend solely on the type/application code given in the first part of the code and are so numerous as to be impossible to indicate here.
[src:en-3/en-10027] Additional symbols are separated from the main code by the plus sign (+).
[src:en-3/en-10027] The most common additional symbols are the impact and temperature codes for structural steels, category 1 - Sxxx.
[src:en-3/en-10027] In addition to the descriptive steel grade naming system indicated above, within EN 10027-2 is defined a system for creating unique steel grade numbers.
[src:en-3/en-10027] While less descriptive and intuitive than the grand names they are easier to tabulate and use in data processing applications.
[src:en-3/en-10027] The number is in the following format: x.yyzz(zz) Where x is the material type (only 1 is specified so far), yy is the steel group number (specified in EN10027-2) and zz(zz) is a sequential number designated by the certifying body, the number in brackets being unused but reserved for later use.
[src:en-3/en-10027] The current certification body is the VDEh in Düsseldorf, Germany.
[src:en-3/en-10027] Below is a table comparing steel grades from different grading systems.
[src:en-3/en-10027] The American Petroleum Institute has a standardized steel grading system for various properties of steel composites.
[src:en-3/en-10027] In order to clearly distinguish the steel grade, tubing, casing and its coupling should be painted with color codes respectively.
[src:en-3/en-10027] Color bands should be painted on tubing and casing body longer than 600mm to either end.
[src:en-3/en-10027] The whole outer-body of the coupling needs to be painted color and then color codes.
[src:en-3/en-10027] API 5B and 5CT provide various steel grades and color codes of each grade, with general information of casing and tubing.
[src:en-3/en-10080] The **EN 10080: Steel for the reinforcement of concrete** is a European Standard.
[src:en-3/en-10080] Steel conforming to this standard has a corrugated, periodically profiled or smooth surface.
[src:en-3/en-10080] This standard does not define technical grades.
[src:en-3/en-1063] The protective strength of a glazed shielding is rated based on the type of munitions, or threat level, it is capable of withstanding.
[src:en-3/en-1063] There are 7 main standard threat levels: BR1-BR7 (also written as B1-B7), each corresponding to a different type of small arms fire.
[src:en-3/en-1063] Additionally, there are two other threat levels (SG1 & SG2) corresponding to shotgun munitions.
[src:en-3/en-1063] To be given a particular rating, the glazing must stop the bullet for the specified number of strikes, with multiple strikes placed within 120mm of each other in the test sample which dimensions are 500±5mm x 500±5mm.
[src:en-3/en-1063] The glazing should also be shatterproof and produce no spalls after each strike.
[src:en-3/en-1063] Lastly, the classification levels are numbered in order of increasing protective strength.
[src:en-3/en-1063] Thus any sample complying with the requirements of one class also complies with the requirements of previous classes.
[src:en-3/en-1063] However, the SG (shotgun) classes do not necessarily comply with BR classes.
[src:en-3/en-1078] The standard was revised in 2012, and then amended the same year, into the **EN 1078:2012+A1:2012** standard.
[src:en-3/en-1078] This again was the basis of the identical British standard *BS EN 1078:2012+A1:2012*.
[src:en-3/en-1078] EN 1078 specifies requirements and test methods for bicycle helmets, skateboard and roller skate helmets.
[src:en-3/en-1078] It covers helmet construction including field of vision, shock absorbing properties, retention system properties including chin strap and fastening devices, as well as marking and information.
[src:en-3/en-1078] A derived standard, EN 1080, covers helmets for young children.
[src:en-3/en-1078] It addresses problems associated with the strangulation of children playing while wearing helmets.
[src:en-3/en-3] European standard **EN 3** specifies requirements for portable fire extinguishers.
[src:en-3/en-3] Compliance with the standard is legally required for the construction of all fire extinguishers in the European Union.
[src:en-3/en-3] EN 3-1, EN 3-2, EN 3-4 and EN 3-5 have been withdrawn and were replaced by EN 3-7, EN 3-8 and EN 3-9.
[src:en-3/en-3] EN 3-6 has been withdrawn and was replaced by EN 3-10.
